        <div class="how-card">
            <h2>How Hiragana and Katakana Match</h2>
            <p>Hiragana (ひらがな) and katakana (カタカナ) are the two kana syllabaries in Japanese. They represent the same basic sounds, but each script has a different role. Hiragana is used for native Japanese words, grammar endings, particles, and pronunciation guides. Katakana is used for foreign names, loanwords, emphasis, onomatopoeia, and many technical terms.</p>

            <p>Because the sound values match, most hiragana characters can be converted directly into their katakana equivalent. For example, <strong>あ</strong> becomes <strong>ア</strong>, <strong>き</strong> becomes <strong>キ</strong>, and <strong>が</strong> becomes <strong>ガ</strong>. Small kana such as <strong>っ</strong>, <strong>ゃ</strong>, <strong>ゅ</strong>, and <strong>ょ</strong> also convert to their katakana forms.</p>

            <div class="reading-example">
                <div class="kanji-big" aria-hidden="true">あ</div>
                <div class="readings">
                    <strong>Hiragana:</strong> <span>ひらがな</span><br>
                    <strong>Katakana:</strong> <span>ヒラガナ</span><br>
                    <strong>Same sounds:</strong> <span>hi-ra-ga-na</span> in both scripts
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>This converter performs a direct Unicode-based kana transformation in your browser. It changes only hiragana and katakana characters, so kanji, romaji, numbers, punctuation, and spacing stay exactly where they are.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

